AB The diagnosis, management and prognosis of 17 infants with cystic
   fibrosis  (CF) and severe respiratory disease were reviewed for the
   period 1968 to 1972.  The clinical course of these infants was
   characterized by a bronchiolitis-like syndrome with failure to
   thrive and malnutrition.  Arterial blood gases demonstrated marked
   hypoxemia (mean PaO2, 36.5 mm Hg).  Tracheal cultures showed a
   predominance of gram-negative microorganisms with Pseudomonas
   aeruginosa, Klebsiella pneumoniae and Escherichia coli
   predominating.  Corticosteroids were used in all patients.  Despite
   vigorous therapy including antibiotics there was a 60% mortality.
   A delay in the diagnosis of CF from the onset if respiratory
   symptoms with a mean of six weeks was considered an important factor
   affecting survival.  This data supports the need for developing a
   reliable screen test for CF at birth.
